Grocery Sales Forecasting

Xilai Li, Shawn Hu, Shihan Li, Tianming Zhang

project overview

  1. Goal:to predict unit sales for each item from our randomly selected 82 items
  2. Data selection methodology: due the the extremely large nature of all the datasets in our kaggle project, we randomly selected 82 items, 2% of total items for our modeling
  3. Modeling methodlogy: we have used four linear regression models. First, we included every variable into our model as our base model. Second model we eminated all the variables that are collinear with other variables in our model to increase our efficiency. Third we estimate our model by using the weighted oil price to improve our our model efficiency based on two metrics R^2 and RMSE. eventually, we derive our final model by adding a quadratic variable oil price^2.

holidays <- holidays %>% 
  filter(transferred == "False")
local_holidays <- holidays %>% 
  filter(locale == "Local" | locale == "Regional") %>% 
  transmute(date = date, state = locale_name, holiday_type1 = type)
national_holidays <- holidays %>% 
  filter(locale == "National") %>% 
  transmute(date = date, holiday_type2 = type)

Data preparation

Now, lets merge all sub-datasets, turn categorical variables into factors and create a new variable month.

head(oil, 30)

We realized that the oil dataset has missing dates (this might be caused by the fact that the stock market is closed for Saturdays and Sundays). Merging this dataset with the training data might cause a large proportion of NA. To deal with that, we decide to use the mean value of oil price on the days before and after the missing date to represent the NA value.

transactions$date <- as.character(transactions$date)
local_holidays$date <- as.character(local_holidays$date)
national_holidays$date <- as.character(national_holidays$date)
local_holidays$state <- as.character(local_holidays$state)
stores$state <- as.character(stores$state)
oil$date <- as.character(oil$date)

preparedata <- function(data){
  data <- data %>% 
  left_join(stores, by = "store_nbr") %>% 
  left_join(items, by = "item_nbr") %>% 
  left_join(transactions, by = c("date", "store_nbr")) %>% 
  left_join(oil, by="date") %>% 
  left_join(local_holidays, by = c("date", "state")) %>% 
  left_join(national_holidays, by = "date")
data$holiday_type1 <- as.character(data$holiday_type1)
data$holiday_type2 <- as.character(data$holiday_type2)
data$holiday_type <- ifelse(is.na(data$holiday_type1), data$holiday_type2, data$holiday_type1)
data$isholiday <- with(data, ifelse(is.na(holiday_type), 0, 1))
data$holiday_type[is.na(data$holiday_type)] <- "Not holiday"
data$dcoilwtico <- ifelse(is.na(data$dcoilwtico), mean(data$dcoilwtico[(which(is.na(data$dcoilwtico))-2):(which(is.na(data$dcoilwtico))+2)], na.rm = TRUE), data$dcoilwtico)
data <- select(data, -id, -holiday_type1, -holiday_type2)
data$month <- month(as.Date(data$date))

data$date <- as.factor(data$date)
data$store_nbr <- as.factor(data$store_nbr)
data$item_nbr <- as.factor(data$item_nbr)
data$onpromotion <- as.factor(data$onpromotion)
data$city <- as.factor(data$city)
data$state <- as.factor(data$state)
data$type <- as.factor(data$type)
data$cluster <- as.factor(data$cluster)
data$family <- as.factor(data$family)
data$class <- as.factor(data$class)
data$perishable <- as.factor(data$perishable)
data$holiday_type <- as.factor(data$holiday_type)
data$isholiday <- as.factor(data$isholiday)
data$month <- as.factor(data$month)
return(data)
}

multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) {
  require(grid)

  # Make a list from the ... arguments and plotlist
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)

  numPlots = length(plots)

  # If layout is NULL, then use 'cols' to determine layout
  if (is.null(layout)) {
    # Make the panel
    # ncol: Number of columns of plots
    # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols
    layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)),
                    ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols))
  }

 if (numPlots==1) {
    print(plots[[1]])
 } else {
    # Set up the page
    grid.newpage()
    pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))

    # Make each plot, in the correct location
    for (i in 1:numPlots) {
      # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot
      matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))

      print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx$row,
                                      layout.pos.col = matchidx$col))
    }
  }
}

Modeling

Data splitting

  1. we set see to 100 to make sure that our data can be reproduced
  2. we split the model data into training and testing sets.
set.seed(100)
inTraining <- createDataPartition(final_data_model$item_nbr, p=0.7, list=FALSE)
train_data <- final_data_model[inTraining,]
test_data <- final_data_model[-inTraining,]

Correlation analysis

1.Before we run our base model, we looked at correlation table to check collinearity among all variables. 2. we used our correlation analysis to get rid of variables with high multi-collinearity to make our model are efficient and simple. 3. load the library and run our correlation analysis

library(GoodmanKruskal)
varSet <- c("item_nbr", "store_nbr", "onpromotion", "city", "state", "type", "class", "family", "cluster", "perishable", "isholiday", "month")
Corframe <- subset(final_data_model, select = varSet)
Cormatrix <- GKtauDataframe(Corframe)
plot(Cormatrix)

conclusion from our correlation anlysis

  1. we found store_nbr is highly correlated with city, state, type and cluster;
  2. item_nbr is highly correlated with class, family and perishable;
  3. city is highly correlated with state; cluster is highly correlated with type;
  4. class and family are highly correlated with family and perishable.
  5. Therefore, when we take fixed effects in the linear regression model, we have to be very careful to figure out which variable to include and which variable to exclude.
  6. we should not regress our dependent variable on multiple highly-correlated predictors simutaneously.
  7. For example, if we use store-fixed effect, we would eliminate state and city in our model. If we use item-fixed effect, we would get rid of class, family and perishable.

Base model

1, we run a base model with every variable in the our sample dataset 2. the model summary tells us that coefficients for city, state, type and class are NA. And R square is 0.1923 Na tells us the there are lots of collinear variables in our model.

evaluation of our base model

we wrote a function to calculate Root-Mean Sqaure Error. We calculate the RMSE for model 1, it is 13.25.

rmse <- function(error){
  sqrt(mean(error^2, na.rm = TRUE))
}

error_mod1 <- test_data$unit_sales - pred1
rmse_mod1 <- rmse(error_mod1)

refine the base model

1.we refine our model by excluding city, state, type, cluster, class, family, perishable and isholiday to eliminate collinearity 2.our model 2 summary tells us that almost all variables are statistically significant and R square is 0.1921. which is clsoe to previous model.
